Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Manager of Digital Publications Regina , SK Description Manager of Digital Publications– Full-time The Legislative Assembly Service of Saskatchewan (LAS) provides the administration and support required for the operation of the Legislative Assembly and provides organizational continuity from one Legislature to the next. The Parliamentary Publications branch exists to produce the Debates and Proceedings, publishes indexes and support various digital publishing initiatives of the official records of the Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan. This role develops and maintains digital publishing features and services for the LAS, including official records and other documents produced by the Parliamentary Support Division; oversees all digital publications to ensure digital publication standards are met; creates, organizes and structures information hierarchies underlying digital publications; and performs ongoing formatting and tagging of parliamentary publications while creating workflows and quality assurance processes. Our candidate of choice will require knowledge of information management goals, practices, and concepts; controlled vocabularies and information ontologies; XML schemata, particularly those suited to legislative information (e.g., Akoma Ntoso, Dublin Core, or Parliamentary Metadata Language); familiarity with XML authoring software (e.g., oXygen); web-based publication practices, with an understanding of user experience design, accessibility requirements, and data retrieval optimization; internet protocols (e.g., HTTP, FTP, TCP);
information and document management software; XML, HTML and other markup languages (e.g. XSLT); cascading style sheets (CSS); parliamentary procedure and publications. Knowledge of design and graphics software (e.g., InDesign) and conversion software (e.g., Omnimark, Prince XML) would be considered an asset. This knowledge would typically be acquired in a post-secondary degree or post-graduate diploma in information science, knowledge management, digital humanities, systems analysis, digital publishing, or information technology. A strong understanding of the legislative process and Saskatchewan’s Legislative Assembly, and an awareness of current affairs and Saskatchewan history would be assets. This position requires a criminal record check as a condition of employment. All employees of the Legislative Assembly Service are required to provide non-partisan, confidential service to all Members of the Legislative Assembly. To learn more about the LAS, our vision, mission and values, and to find further information about the position, salary and benefits, please visit www.legassembly.sk.ca/about/employmentIf you are interested in this opportunity, please submit a cover letter and resume by 5:00 p.m. (CST) May 12, 2023 to:
